✅ Your Flow Process: Vertical Trigger + Horizontal Deep Link
🔧 Example: feature-block.welcome
Path 1 → text-message(greeting) → First message, always shown

Path 2 → generic-template(options) → Second message, shows buttons like “View Products”, “Ask Question”

🔗 Horizontal Deep Link
Each button in Path 2 links to another flow via payload:

payload: flow_product_cream

payload: flow_service_booking

🧠 Interpretation
Vertical paths = sequential messages inside the same block

Horizontal links = deep connections to other flows via payload

This is correct and efficient. It separates:

Content delivery (vertical)

Flow navigation (horizontal)

🧭 Alternative: Horizontal Flow Chain
Some platforms (like Dialogflow, ManyChat, or Rasa) use a horizontal chaining model:

text
Flow 1 → Flow 2 → Flow 3 → End
Each flow ends with a trigger or condition that launches the next. This works well for:

Linear onboarding

Multi-step forms

Escalation flows

But it can be harder to manage for Khmer admins because:

It’s less visual

Harder to reuse blocks

Requires strict condition logic

🧠 Best Practice Comparison
Platform	Flow Style	Notes
KhmerAi.Chat (yours)	Vertical paths + horizontal deep links	✅ Easy for admins, reusable blocks, Messenger-safe
Dialogflow	Intent → Fulfillment → Context	Powerful NLP, but complex for non-technical users
ManyChat	Button → Flow → Action	Visual, but limited reuse and hard to scale
Rasa	Stories + Rules + Actions	Great for developers, but not admin-friendly
Facebook Messenger	Templates + payloads	Requires strict format, no native flow builder
